<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-04-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="690" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d690">
                    <head>No. 686.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-04-07"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 7,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 205.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your No.
                        371, in which you inclose an extract from the Berne newspaper Der Bund,
                        respecting the action of the commune of Böttstein, Switzerland, in sending
                        to America an imbecile young woman, name not given, who had hitherto been
                        supported by that commune; and to approve your communication of the facts to
                        the collector of the port of New York, whither, it was understood, she had
                        been sent.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>